        id: "distillation_unit",
        name: "Distillation Unit",
        purpose: "**Pure water production** aur **Kjeldahl ammonia distillation** ke liye:\n\n**Water Purity Grades for Dairy Lab:**\n| Grade | Conductivity | Use |\n|---|---|---|\n| Type III (Distilled) | <1 µS/cm | General lab use, media preparation |\n| Type II (Double distilled/DI) | <0.1 µS/cm | Buffer preparation, sensitive assays |\n| Type I (Ultrapure/Milli-Q) | <0.056 µS/cm | HPLC mobile phase, molecular biology |\n\n**Impurities Removed by Distillation:**\n- Dissolved mineral salts (Na⁺, Ca²⁺, Mg²⁺, Cl⁻, SO₄²⁻)\n- Non-volatile organics\n- Particulate matter, bacteria (mostly)\n\n**What Distillation CANNOT Remove:**\n- Volatile organics (boiling point similar to water) — e.g., chloroform, toluene\n- Dissolved gases (CO₂, O₂) — partially removed\n- For these: deionization + activated carbon filtration needed",
        principle: "**Selective Phase Change (Liquid → Gas → Liquid)** based on volatility differences.\n\n**Thermodynamic Principle:**\nRaoult's Law (for ideal solutions):\n$$P_A = x_A \cdot P_A^*$$\nWhere:\n- $P_A$ = partial pressure of water\n- $x_A$ = mole fraction of water\n- $P_A^*$ = vapor pressure of pure water\n\nAt boiling point, total vapor pressure = atmospheric pressure:\n$$P_{total} = P_{H_2O} + P_{impurities} = P_{atm}$$\n\nNon-volatile impurities (salts) have essentially zero vapor pressure → they stay in liquid phase. Only water evaporates.\n\n**Distillation Still Components:**\n1. **Boiling Flask/Evaporator:** Water boiled at 100°C (at 1 atm)\n2. **Condenser (Liebig/Graham/Allihn type):**\n   - Cooling water flows countercurrent to steam\n   - Heat exchange: $Q = m_{steam} \times \lambda_{vap}$ where $\lambda_{vap}(water) = 2257\\ J/g$\n   - Steam condensed → pure distillate\n3. **Collection Vessel:** Borosilicate glass (chemically inert)\n\n**Distillation Rate:**\n$$\\dot{m}_{distillate} = \\frac{P_{heater}}{\\lambda_{vap}} \\approx \\frac{1000W}{2257\\ J/g} \\approx 0.44\\ g/s = 1.6\\ L/hr$$\n\n**Kjeldahl Distillation Unit (Specialized):**\n- **Steam generator** → steam injection into Kjeldahl flask\n- **Digested sample + NaOH → NH₃ liberation:**\n$$NH_4^+ + OH^- \\rightarrow NH_3 \\uparrow + H_2O$$\n- **Condenser** → NH₃ condensed\n- **Receiver flask (boric acid):**\n$$NH_3 + H_3BO_3 \\rightarrow (NH_4)^+H_2BO_3^-$$\n- Distillation rate: 5–7 mL/min for 4 minutes (total ~25 mL distillate collected)",
