        id: "ftir",
        name: "Fourier-Transform Infrared Spectroscopy (FTIR)",
        purpose: "**Chemical fingerprinting** aur **adulteration detection** ke liye:\n\n**Dairy Lab Applications:**\n- **Ghee Adulteration Detection:**\n  - Vanaspati/partially hydrogenated fat: Trans fat peaks at **966 cm⁻¹** (C-H out-of-plane bending of trans double bonds)\n  - Animal body fat (tallow): Different triglyceride profile\n- **Milk Powder Composition:** Fat, protein, lactose simultaneous quantification\n- **Milk Adulteration:** Detergent, urea, starch, melamine detection\n- **Cheese Authenticity:** Distinguishing cow vs. buffalo vs. goat milk cheese\n- **Fat Oxidation Monitoring:** Peroxide formation — carbonyl peak at **1720–1745 cm⁻¹**\n\n**Key Spectral Regions:**\n| Wavenumber (cm⁻¹) | Bond/Group | Significance |\n|---|---|---|\n| 3200–3600 | O-H stretch | Water, alcohols |\n| 2800–3000 | C-H stretch | Fatty acid chains |\n| 1700–1750 | C=O stretch (ester) | Triglycerides, Fat |\n| 1540–1560 | N-H bend (Amide II) | Proteins |\n| 1000–1200 | C-O-C stretch | Carbohydrates/Lactose |\n| 966 | C-H trans bend | Trans fatty acids |",
        principle: "**Molecular Vibrational Spectroscopy using Michelson Interferometer.**\n\n**Molecular Vibration Fundamentals:**\nBonds in molecules vibrate at characteristic frequencies:\n$$\\tilde{\\nu} = \\frac{1}{2\\pi c}\\sqrt{\\frac{k}{\\mu}}$$\nWhere:\n- $\\tilde{\\nu}$ = wavenumber (cm⁻¹)\n- $c$ = speed of light\n- $k$ = force constant of bond (N/m) — bond strength\n- $\\mu$ = reduced mass = $\\frac{m_1 \\cdot m_2}{m_1 + m_2}$\n\n**Key Insight:** Stronger bonds (C≡C > C=C > C-C) aur lighter atoms → **higher frequency** vibrations → higher wavenumber absorption\n\n**Michelson Interferometer Operation:**\n1. **Beamsplitter** IR beam ko do beams mein divide karta hai\n2. Ek beam **fixed mirror** par jaata hai, doosra **moving mirror** par\n3. Dono beams wapas reflect hokar **recombine** hote hain → **interference pattern** banata hai\n4. Moving mirror ki position change karne se, alag-alag wavelengths constructively ya destructively interfere karte hain\n5. Result: ek **Interferogram** — optical path difference vs. intensity plot\n\n**Fourier Transform:**\n$$S(\\tilde{\\nu}) = \\int_{-\\infty}^{\\infty} I(\\delta) \\cdot e^{-2\\pi i \\tilde{\\nu} \\delta}\\ d\\delta$$\nWhere:\n- $S(\\tilde{\\nu})$ = Spectrum (absorbance vs. wavenumber)\n- $I(\\delta)$ = Interferogram (intensity vs. optical path difference $\\delta$)\n\n**Why FTIR is better than Dispersive IR:**\n- **Fellgett's Advantage (Multiplex advantage):** Saari wavelengths simultaneously measure hoti hain → faster\n- **Jacquinot's Advantage:** Larger aperture → more light throughput → better signal-to-noise\n- **Connes' Advantage:** Laser-referenced position → wavenumber accuracy better than 0.01 cm⁻¹\n\n**ATR-FTIR (Attenuated Total Reflectance):**\nModern dairy analysis mein most common:\n- Sample (liquid milk) ko ek **ATR crystal (ZnSe, Germanium, Diamond)** par rakha jaata hai\n- IR beam crystal mein internally reflect hoti hai → **evanescent wave** sample ke andar ~1–2 µm deep penetrate karta hai\n- No sample preparation needed — direct measurement of liquid milk!\n- Mid-IR region (4000–400 cm⁻¹) scan: **<30 seconds**",
