        id: "gc",
        name: "Gas Chromatograph (GC)",
        purpose: "**Volatile compound analysis** — dairy science mein primary applications:\n\n**1. Fatty Acid Profile (FAME Analysis) — Most Important:**\n- **Saturated Fatty Acids (SFA):** C4:0 (Butyric), C6:0 (Caproic), C8:0 (Caprylic), C10:0, C12:0, C14:0, C16:0 (Palmitic), C18:0 (Stearic)\n- **Monounsaturated (MUFA):** C18:1 (Oleic acid)\n- **Polyunsaturated (PUFA):** C18:2 (Linoleic), C18:3 (Linolenic)\n- **Conjugated Linoleic Acid (CLA, C18:2 c9,t11):** Bioactive compound in dairy fat\n- **Trans Fatty Acids:** C18:1t (Elaidic) — adulterant indicator\n\n**2. Flavor/Off-flavor Compounds:**\n- **Rancidity:** Aldehydes (hexanal, nonanal), ketones (2-heptanone), free fatty acids\n- **Fermentation flavors:** Diacetyl (butter flavor), acetaldehyde (yogurt)\n- **Heated milk flavors:** Furfural, HMF (Hydroxymethylfurfural)\n\n**3. Residues:**\n- Pesticide residues (organochlorine, organophosphate)\n- Solvent residues in milk powder\n\n**Indian Standard:** IS 548 (Fat analysis), FSSAI methods",
        principle: "**Differential Partitioning of Compounds Between Mobile (Gas) and Stationary (Liquid) Phases.**\n\n**Chromatographic Theory:**\n\n**Van Deemter Equation** (Plate Height vs. carrier gas velocity):\n$$H = A + \\frac{B}{u} + C \cdot u$$\nWhere:\n- $H$ = Height Equivalent to a Theoretical Plate (HETP) — smaller is better\n- $A$ = Eddy diffusion (multi-path term) — packing irregularity\n- $B$ = Longitudinal diffusion term — diffusion along column\n- $C$ = Mass transfer resistance — speed of equilibration\n- $u$ = Linear velocity of carrier gas\n\n**Optimal carrier gas velocity** minimizes H → best separation\n\n**Retention & Separation:**\n**Retention Factor (k):**\n$$k = \\frac{t_R - t_M}{t_M}$$\nWhere $t_R$ = retention time of compound, $t_M$ = dead time (unretained compound)\n\n**Separation Factor (α) between two compounds:**\n$$\alpha = \\frac{k_2}{k_1}$$\n\n**Resolution (R):**\n$$R_s = \\frac{2(t_{R2} - t_{R1})}{w_1 + w_2} = \\frac{\\sqrt{N}}{4} \\cdot \\frac{\\alpha - 1}{\\alpha} \\cdot \\frac{k}{1+k}$$\nWhere $N$ = number of theoretical plates, $w$ = peak width\n\n**FAME Analysis Procedure:**\n\n**Sample Preparation (Methylation):**\n$$\\text{Triglyceride (Fat)} + CH_3OH \\xrightarrow{BF_3\\ or\\ NaOMe\\ catalyst} \\text{FAME} + \\text{Glycerol}$$\nFAMEs are volatile → suitable for GC analysis\n\n**GC Conditions for FAME:**\n- **Column:** SP-2560 or BPX-70 (polar capillary column, 100m × 0.25mm × 0.2µm film)\n- **Column Temperature:** 60°C → 240°C (temperature gradient program)\n- **Carrier Gas:** Helium, 1.2 mL/min\n- **Detector:** FID (Flame Ionization Detector)\n  - H₂ + Air flame at 300°C\n  - Carbon compounds produce ions in flame → current measured\n  - Response factor proportional to carbon atoms\n  - $$i = \\frac{q \\cdot \\dot{m}_C}{F}$$\n  where $q$ = charge per carbon atom, $\\dot{m}_C$ = carbon mass flow rate\n\n**Identification:** Retention time match with FAME standard mixture (e.g., Supelco 37 FAME Mix)\n**Quantification:** Area normalization method\n$$\\%FA_i = \\frac{A_i}{\\sum A_i} \\times 100$$",
